    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Lingering Questions About Iraq</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Zuriel Shiv letter warns there will be no painless exit from Iraq, and US should be planning for swift, complete transfer of authority to UN Security Council</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>There will be no painless exit from Iraq. In ''A Troubled Occupation in Iraq'' (editorial, July 10), you assert that the pressure on your troops can be eased ''once Washington embraces a more substantial role for the United Nations'' and add, ''With broader U.N. involvement, American and British troops will seem less like foreign conquerors and occupiers.''</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>There will be no painless exit from Iraq. In ''A Troubled Occupation in Iraq'' (editorial, July 10), you assert that the pressure on your troops can be eased ''once Washington embraces a more substantial role for the United Nations'' and add, ''With broader U.N. involvement, American and British troops will seem less like foreign conquerors and occupiers.''</p>
        <p>One can understand someone like Secretary of Defense Donald H. Rumsfeld defending a policy of playing solo in Iraq, but what you are suggesting is a half-hearted, or rather face-saving, measure.</p>
        <p>What the United States should be doing, for its own as well as the general good, is a swift and complete transfer of authority in Iraq, under a clear-cut mandate, to the Security Council -- for the same reasons you bring up.</p>
        <p>But no! According to the ''March of Folly'' theory, your president will carry the United States until the bitter end of your solitary presence there.</p>
        <p>ZURIEL SHIV  Holon, Israel, July 10, 2003</p>
      </block>
